## Final case study (~300 words, opens with screen-time number)

**Focus Flow**

7-8 hours a day of screen time, down to 4-5. One day, 3 hours 14 minutes. That's not a projection — that's my own phone, before and after I built this.

**The problem.** I get distracted. So do a lot of people. I wanted to know exactly how many hours I was spending on productive work versus how many I was losing — so I built Focus Flow to answer that for myself first.

**What I did.** I designed it from scratch. Most task managers use red or orange — I used a nature rain background instead, calmer, and it helped me focus. A task bar with three priority levels: high, medium, low. A Pomodoro timer, 45 on and 15 off by default, adjustable by the user. A music session with four options — Lofi Girl, Lofi Boy, a 10-hour rain sound, or a custom playlist. Both timers minimize and move around the screen. It started small: a chat-feature task in Vercel v0 during my internship at FlyRank AI. I finished it and decided to build the whole thing out — Next.js 14, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS.

I also tried an AI agent for task entry — type "/task xyz /priority medium" and it sorts it for you, or "/song" to loop a track. It didn't work. I'm still working on it.

**What came of it.** It works. I've used it many times and I'm about to deploy it. Even at 5-6 hours of study a day, I wasn't satisfied — my own target kept going up.

Next time, I'd add a live 4K rain wallpaper, get the chatbot actually working, and build a stopwatch to track total study hours in one continuous count.

